Loan Data from Prosper Exploration¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

I am seeing some nan values from CreditGrade and EmploymentStatus. Next, I will replace these values with "Not available".

In [13]:
na_mask = loan_copy['EmploymentStatus'].isna()
loan_copy.loc[na_mask, 'EmploymentStatus'] = 'Not available'

In [15]:
# Time to repeat the same process for CreditGrade. Replace nan with "Not available". 
# While doing so, I also noticed a value called "NC", which could cause confusion for readers. 
# For simplicity and more clarity, I will change it to "No credit"
na_mask_2 = loan_copy['CreditGrade'].isna()
loan_copy.loc[na_mask_2, 'CreditGrade'] = 'Not available'
na_mask_3 = loan_copy['CreditGrade'] == 'NC'
loan_copy.loc[na_mask_3, 'CreditGrade'] = 'No credit'

In [17]:
# Time to convert the clean variables to ordered categorical types.
ordinal_var_dict = {'ProsperRating (Alpha)': ['HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA'],
                    'CreditGrade':['Not available','No credit','HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA'],
                   'EmploymentStatus': ['Not available','Not employed','Retired','Other','Employed','Part-time','Self-employed','Full-time'],
                    'LoanStatus':['Cancelled','Chargedoff','Defaulted','Past Due (>120 days)',
                                  'Past Due (91-120 days)','Past Due (61-90 days)',
                                  'Past Due (31-60 days)','Past Due (16-30 days)',
                                  'Past Due (1-15 days)','FinalPaymentInProgress',
                                  'Current','Completed']
       
                   }
# Below I will use a for loop to reduce repetitive code (as instructed by the project rubric)
for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, 
                                               categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    loan_copy[var] = loan_copy[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan. The variables are a good mix of quantitative variables (e.g. BorrowerAPR, ProsperRating (numeric), and LoanOriginalAmount) and categorical variables (e.g. EmploymentStatus, Occupation, and ProsperRating (Alpha)).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

As a potential borrower, I'm most interested in the factors that go into getting the lowest Borrower APR possible so that I can save money on interests and fees if I take out loans from Prosper in the future. The analysis below revealed that Borrower APR has a strong negative correlation with ProsperRating (numeric) at -0.962, meaning that the higher Prosper rates you, the lower your APR is likely to be; however, as an individual borrower, I don't have visibility into how Prosper rates me internally and I would like to find out what I can monitor to make sure I have good Prosper Rating and in turn a lower Borrower APR in the future.

Meanwhile, I am also interested in seeing what size of loans do borrowers usually take out from Prosper and if the size varies under different scenarios. The reason why I'm interested in this particular topic is that, say my friend is looking to buy a house and asks me if Prosper typically gives out $100-200K loans and if yes, what type of people does this size usually goes to, I could point to my analysis and tell her the answer.

Another area of interests is that what type of people usually default on loans, what's their occupation?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your features of interest?¶

I expect that ProsperRating (numeric) will have the strongest effect on Borrower APR. Prosper assigns APR rates to different borrowers using their internal Prosper Rating as a guide. I also think that credit score, stated monthly income, term, and Employment Status will have effects on the Borrower APR, but we will need to investigate further in the later analysis.

In regards to the Original Loan Amount, I think borrower APR could have a negative impact on it (the borrower might take advantage of the low APR to take out more loans); other factors that worth investigating are credit score and credit length (the difference between DateCreditPulled and FirstRecordedCreditLine).

Moving on to default rate, it might be interesting to look at the default rate for each occupation to see which occupation has the highest default or past due rate and if that "bad debt" rate is correlated with that occupation's mean income.

# I also would like to investigate why do people take out loans. What's the money for? 
# By examining the Listing Category variable, I noticed that it is in numbers and hard to decipher, so I decided to 
# convert listing Category to clear and self-explanatory ones.
loan_copy['ListingCategory (numeric)'] = loan_copy['ListingCategory (numeric)'].astype(str)
listing_details = {
    '0':'Not Available',
    '1':'Debt Consolidation',
    '2':'Home Improvement',
    '3':'Business',
    '4':'Personal Loan',
    '5':'Student Use',
    '6':'Auto',
    '7':'Other',
    '8':'Baby & Adoption',
    '9':'Boat',
    '10':'Cosmetic Procedure',
    '11':'Engagement Ring', 
    '12':'Green Loans',
    '13':'Household Expenses', 
    '14':'Large Purchases', 
    '15':'Medical/Dental', 
    '16':'Motorcycle', 
    '17': 'RV', 
    '18':'Taxes', 
    '19': 'Vacation',
    '20': 'Wedding Loans'
    }

# Function to apply
def abbreviate_source(loan_copy):
    if loan_copy['ListingCategory (numeric)'] in listing_details.keys():
        abbrev = listing_details[loan_copy['ListingCategory (numeric)']]
        return abbrev
    else:
        return loan_copy['ListingCategory (numeric)']
    
loan_copy['ListingCategory (numeric)'] = loan_copy.apply(abbreviate_source, axis=1)

Adjustments:

When examining the Listing Category variable, I noticed that it is in number format and hard to decipher, so I decided to convert listing Category to clear and self-explanatory ones.

Change the form:

I created two new variables.

  1. average credit score: I averaged CreditScoreRangeLower and CreditScoreRangeUpper to form a single variable.
  2. Credit History Length: take the difference between DateCreditPulled and FirstRecordedCreditLine to measure this borrower's credit history length. We want to include this variable because it usually is an important factor to credit scores.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Our area of interest is to find out the factors that go into getting the lowest Borrower APR possible.

Borrower APR and Prosper Rating have a strong negative correlation!:

  • Borrower APR had a high correlation with Prosper Rating. When Prosper Rating increases, we tend to see a lower Borrower APR.

That's good to know but individual borrowers do not have visibility into Prosper Rating:

  • Prosper Rating is an internal rating that Prosper assigns to loan applicants and it is challenging to find out their own Prosper Rating if the borrowers are new to applying for loans. Are there any factors that customers have easy access to that may have a good correlation with the APR they could expect to receive from Prosper? The answer is yes -- credit score and available bank card credit! For credit score, this analysis takes the average of the CreditScoreRangeLower and CreditScoreRangeUpper variables and created a new variable called average_credit_score, which saw a moderate -0.43 correlation with Borrower's APR. On the other hand, available bank card credit and Borrower APR had a -0.349r.

For individual borrowers, it might be a good idea to monitor:

  • credit scores: a lot of credit card apps allow customers to check their FICO scores. The higher the credit score, the lower the APR.
  • available bank card credit: borrowers can easily calculate this by opening up their credit card apps. The higher the available bank card credit, the lower the APR.

Employment status-wise, it certainly helps to have a full time job (at least a part-time one), having a job means that the borrower's APR could go down from 0.28 to 0.20!

It also helps if the borrower is a home owner! We are seeing a lower median borrower APR from home owners vs. non-home owners.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main features of interest?¶

  • Prosper rating and average credit score have a moderate positive correlation of 0.549. The higher the credit score, the higher the prosper rating.
  • Loan original amount also saw a moderate positive correlation with Prosper rating at 0.429. The higher the prosper rating , the more loan original amount we tend to see.

# next I will consolidate the six past due status into one status: Past Due.
# Convert Current or Completed into one status: Healthy
loan_status_abbrev = {
       'Current':'Healthy: Current or Completed',
    'Completed':'Healthy: Current or Completed',
    'Defaulted':'Defaulted',
    'Past Due (1-15 days)':'Past Due',
    'Past Due (31-60 days)':'Past Due',
'Past Due (61-90 days)':'Past Due',
'Past Due (91-120 days)':'Past Due',
'Past Due (16-30 days)':'Past Due',
'Past Due (>120 days)':'Past Due'
    }


# Function to apply
def abbreviate_source(loan_copy):
    if loan_copy['LoanStatus'] in loan_status_abbrev.keys():
        abbrev = loan_status_abbrev[loan_copy['LoanStatus']]
        return abbrev
    else:
        return loan_copy['LoanStatus']
    
loan_copy['LoanStatus'] = loan_copy.apply(abbreviate_source, axis=1)

Observations
The graph displays that for high-rating borrowers (A or AA), 60-month loans usually have a higher Borrower APR vs. 12-month loans. This makes sense because the more money you want to borrow, the riskier the transaction is for Prosper and the higher your APR is likely to be.

For B-C borrowers, we did not see Borrower APR varies by loan terms.

When it comes to lower credit rating borrowers (E-D), 12-month loans actually have higher APRs than 60-month ones. This is probably due to the fact that Prosper knows that they are not very likely to pay the full amount back, so giving thse borrowers more time (60 months instead of 12 months) might allow them to repay more debt amount.

Interestingly, for HR customers, only 36 month loans were seen in this dataset.

def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    binsize_x = 25
    bins_x = np.arange(350, loan_copy['average_credit_score'].max()+binsize_x, binsize_x)
    binsize_y = 0.005
    bins_y = np.arange(0.006, loan_copy['BorrowerAPR'].max()+binsize_y, binsize_y)
    plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5)
    x_ticks = np.arange(350, 900+50, 50)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶¶

Home owner vs. non-home owners:

  • Home owners tend to see lower APR because home owners made up for the majority of borrowers with great ratings (B-AA). In comparison, non-home owners made up for the majority for E and D borrowers.

Loan Status:

  • For all Prosper Ratings except for "A", Defaulted loans usually have a higher Borrower APR compared to Healthy or past due ones.

Loan Terms:

  • For high-rating borrowers (A or AA), 60-month loans usually have a higher Borrower APR vs. 12-month loans. This makes sense because the more money you want to borrow, the riskier the transaction is for Prosper and the higher your APR is likely to be.
  • For B-C borrowers, we did not see Borrower APR varies by loan terms.
  • When it comes to lower credit rating borrowers (E-D), 12-month loans actually have higher APRs than 60-month ones. This is probably due to the fact that Prosper knows that they are not very likely to pay the full amount back, so giving thse borrowers more time (60 months instead of 12 months) might allow them to repay more debt amount.
  • Interestingly, for HR customers, only 36 month loans were seen in this dataset.

Employment Status:

  • For AA or HR rating borrowers, we did not see Borrower APR varying by different employment status.
  • For B-A borrowers, part-time workers usually have the cheapest APR, followed by retired.
  • For D-C borrowers, unemployed workers usually have the most expensive APR.
  • For E borrowers, retired workers are seeing a more expensive APR vs. unemployed workers.

Other findings:

  • For Employed, Part-time, Full-time, and Retired, there was an apparent relationship of higher credit score leading to a lower borrower APR; however, for self-employed, not employed, not available, and other, we saw more ambiguous relationships.

Findings in the Occupation dataset:

  • There is a clear negative relationship between bad debt percentage and stated monthly income of an occupation. Prosper is also savvy enough to charge these likely-to-default occupations like students higher APRs (see the dark points on the top left corner of the graph) and charge likely-to-repay occupations lower APRs (see the bright spots on the lower right corner of the graph).
  • The higher the montly income of an occupation, the lower the bad debt percentage is likely to be.
  • The higher the APR, the higher the bad debt percentage.
  • The higher the loan original amount, the lower the bad debt percentage.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Whether the borrower is a homeowner or not does not make a difference in APR under each Prosper Rating group.

In the Bivariate section, I mentioned that if the borrower is a home owner, the median APR is lower than non-home owner, but did not take into account that maybe the homeowner group just houses more high credit rating borrowers whereas the non-homeowners might consist of low credit rating borrowers.
